00:27:04.080 --> 00:27:12.650
Julie Stout: in what had been the office for the U.S. Steel Company. It was now empty, it wasn't really much of anything. Yeah. I could just go there.

185
00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:32.450
Julie Stout: And we had so many, people to look after the kids. It was great. That's awesome. They also became friends, of course. So you built a community there, basically. What? You built a community there? Yes, yeah, we really did, and kept it when they visited in Bloomington as well, so…

186
00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:35.019
Julie Stout: That's awesome. That's good.

187
00:27:35.180 --> 00:27:52.380
Julie Stout: Building on your, like, you mentioned your master's thesis, after you finish your, like, elementary to high school, essentially, can you tell me more about your higher education? Like, where you went to college, what you studied, what you wanted to do for a career?

188
00:27:52.440 --> 00:28:12.380
Julie Stout: In your aspirations in that? Well, it kind of connects, maybe I told you about this too, it connects to my childhood in the sense that, for some reason, I remember riding often in a car with my mother that would go through a neighborhood in Indianapolis that was fairly poverty-stricken, and

189
00:28:12.380 --> 00:28:13.070
Julie Stout: Piss?

190
00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:19.850
Julie Stout: So eagerly wanting to see in the windows, wanting to see what that life was like. And…

191
00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:29.820
Julie Stout: So when I ended up in school, even though I thought I was going to study German, I can't believe why. I would have wanted to study German.

192
00:28:30.300 --> 00:28:35.600
Julie Stout: But,

193
00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:44.000
Julie Stout: I ended up in sociology, which is not that surprising, and I had an incredible teacher, wonderful, wonderful teacher.

194
00:28:44.030 --> 00:29:01.729
Julie Stout: for all of us, I think we all really adored him, and he was a very good teacher, period. What was his name? I do not remember his name, but I do remember my high school teacher's name was Williams, and he was another wonderful teacher. Oh, that's awesome. He was. He's part of my…

195
00:29:01.820 --> 00:29:08.969
Julie Stout: Passwords, Ms. Williams. But I don't remember the other one, unfortunately.

196
00:29:09.430 --> 00:29:25.089
Julie Stout: He would teach in his house, you know, and he was just so easy and relaxed to be with, and taught us very well. And he didn't… he didn't mess with… he didn't mess with statistics or surveys.

197
00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:35.390
Julie Stout: He taught us with novels, which was astounding to me, because that brought Williams together with his literature. He was my English teacher.

198
00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:41.929
Julie Stout: With the sociology, and we read about various ethnic groups, and

199
00:29:43.390 --> 00:29:47.130
Julie Stout: It was good. It was good. And so, when I got to…

200
00:29:47.490 --> 00:29:53.990
Julie Stout: When I got to Colorado, I wanted to see if I could get a job in social work, and I did.

201
00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:58.970
Julie Stout: And there was another community, you know, extended,

202
00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:09.519
Julie Stout: there, because we were all young, we were all in our 20s, 30s, we knew very little about life. And,

203
00:30:09.700 --> 00:30:14.950
Julie Stout: We were the caseworkers for foster children.

204
00:30:15.220 --> 00:30:22.199
Julie Stout: And it was a… It was a very… it was a very deep sort of relationship.

205
00:30:22.630 --> 00:30:28.800
Julie Stout: They came to see me when the kids were… when the kid was… first child was born, yeah.

206
00:30:31.270 --> 00:30:38.339
Julie Stout: And so did… so did another one of them who had been in the Army and made sure to stop by in Bloomington, so…

207
00:30:38.670 --> 00:30:42.130
Julie Stout: Those were… I wish I still was in touch, but I'm not.

208
00:30:43.990 --> 00:30:46.290
Julie Stout: Yeah.

209
00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:55.110
Julie Stout: So then where are we? Oh, you mentioned, you got a job in social work. I got a job in social work, right. And…

210
00:30:56.370 --> 00:31:00.159
Julie Stout: We came back to Bloomington, and only Bruce was working.

211
00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:04.690
Julie Stout: And, I gave birth to my first son.

212
00:31:04.990 --> 00:31:22.819
Julie Stout: And began to kind of be curious about school, and what in the world would… would I do if I went to school, and started thinking about that. And one day, Bruce came home from… from school himself, and he said, there's this department at IU called Folklore.

213
00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:31.650
Julie Stout: And… I thought, well, that's interesting, because I had worked with Blacks, and I had worked with, Mexicans.

214
00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:40.090
Julie Stout: And it… I thought, okay, well, we're going back to Colorado after Bruce finishes, and we'll… this would be good, so…

215
00:31:40.440 --> 00:31:49.489
Julie Stout: That's when I went in and met Dawson, and had not yet been admitted. Can you tell me that story again? About that?

216
00:31:49.510 --> 00:32:06.739
Julie Stout: Well, I waited all summer thinking, well, I'll get an admissions letter, or I'll get a rejection, one or the other, and I hadn't been over the department, I didn't really know anything about it. I know nothing other than what Bruce had told me. It's not like I was looking for it, and…

217
00:32:07.620 --> 00:32:25.930
Julie Stout: So, when I didn't… didn't get admitted, and it was Labor Day, I thought, well, I better go and find out what's going on. So that, for the secretaries downstairs, sent me up to talk to Dr. Dawson, because he was… he was in town… in town that day, and in the department.

218
00:32:26.060 --> 00:32:34.319
Julie Stout: So I walked in and told him that I had applied, but I hadn't gotten any response, and I wasn't sure what was going on and what I should do.

219
00:32:34.520 --> 00:32:38.390
Julie Stout: And so, he… he did something to find out.

220
00:32:38.390 --> 00:32:49.829
Julie Stout: what was going on, and I think he found my admissions form just somewhere, and came up with it, and basically said, you're… you're accepted.

221
00:32:49.830 --> 00:32:58.959
Julie Stout: Right on the spot? Yeah. Yeah. What was your, I'm curious, what was your proposed, like, research topic in that?

222
00:32:59.080 --> 00:33:03.480
Julie Stout: Or what, what did you want to study in the folklore department?

223
00:33:04.430 --> 00:33:10.889
Julie Stout: that first day. Yeah, yeah. That first day, I just wanted to study ethnicity.

224
00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:13.510
Julie Stout: I wanted to study ethnicity.

225
00:33:16.310 --> 00:33:24.139
Julie Stout: And I don't… and there was… there was a Lithuanian displaced person who was teaching folklore. His name was Oinus.

226
00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:30.850
Julie Stout: And so there… there was a connection to the Baltic as well.

227
00:33:33.910 --> 00:33:44.789
Julie Stout: But I don't think I had any particular interest. I had ended up buying a bunch of the books that were… there was a series that Dawson had published on ethnicity.

228
00:33:44.850 --> 00:34:02.050
Julie Stout: folklore in Mexico, folklore in Greece, and things like that, so I figured, well, this is… probably that was my focus, but I didn't have to say anything or declare anything. Yeah. So I just started taking classes.

229
00:34:03.620 --> 00:34:17.389
Julie Stout: Don't ask me who the professors were. That's fine. Do you have any, favorite classes, or not favorite classes that you can remember? Oh, my favorite classes turned out to be in other departments. Really? Yeah.

230
00:34:17.699 --> 00:34:26.480
Julie Stout: In Russian and East European with a fellow who just taught a really wonderful class in Camplit.

231
00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:29.210
Julie Stout: In women's studies?

232
00:34:30.670 --> 00:34:34.290
Julie Stout: And literature.

233
00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:43.729
Julie Stout: So… Because I don't think that folklore stood out very well as teaching at that point.

234
00:34:43.940 --> 00:34:45.380
Julie Stout: Who was there?

235
00:34:45.659 --> 00:34:47.939
Julie Stout: It was a newer program of,

236
00:34:48.540 --> 00:34:51.830
Julie Stout: Newer to some extent around that time, correct?

237
00:34:52.500 --> 00:35:06.280
Julie Stout: I don't think so. No? Oh, newer, just period? Yeah, like, as an actual, like, program and department, because I know it was folded into other departments before then, but of course you probably remember better than me.

238
00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:08.539
Julie Stout: It was part, part of the…

239
00:35:09.080 --> 00:35:12.280
Julie Stout: Yeah, it was… it was part of English.

240
00:35:13.010 --> 00:35:19.589
Julie Stout: was part of English, and then when Dorsen came, he created the folklore Department.

241
00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:22.600
Julie Stout: We can talk about that now or later.

242
00:35:22.970 --> 00:35:25.289
Julie Stout: Let's keep that for later.

243
00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:39.260
Julie Stout: So that kind of leads me to my next batch of… Oh, well, let's finish one more thing, because then I went on for the PhD. Oh, yes, thank you. And that was only because

244
00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:50.320
Julie Stout: I had by then been working for Dorsen. I had done the Gary project. This happened in the 80s, I think. And…

245
00:36:00.670 --> 00:36:07.800
Julie Stout: Let's see… So I'd done these various jobs, and I think by then, Bye.

246
00:36:07.940 --> 00:36:09.250
Julie Stout: Think doors.

247
00:36:10.300 --> 00:36:11.729
Julie Stout: Why was it?

248
00:36:13.970 --> 00:36:18.309
Julie Stout: Oh, I know, he asked me one time, he asked me to put together a CV.

249
00:36:18.470 --> 00:36:19.550
Julie Stout: And…

250
00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:26.119
Julie Stout: I hardly knew, I had no reason to know what a CV was. I'd had one job in my life, and…

251
00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:29.880
Julie Stout: I didn't need a CV for it, I just walked in.

252
00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:31.300
Julie Stout: And…

253
00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:42.530
Julie Stout: So I did, and I realized that then, by then, I had seen some other CVs, and mine was, like, two lines or something. There was just nothing to report. And…

254
00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:53.189
Julie Stout: And then… we started… we expanded from the Gary project to other grants and to other, projects.

255
00:36:53.640 --> 00:37:02.559
Julie Stout: And along came Linda Dag, whom you might have heard about. Hungarian folklore. And she…

256
00:37:02.880 --> 00:37:14.260
Julie Stout: had an idea, too, for a project that would… that would connect Hungary itself with Bloomington. And I became part of that.

257
00:37:14.380 --> 00:37:24.210
Julie Stout: project, and… she said to me one time, she said, you know, you really need to get a PhD.

258
00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:31.129
Julie Stout: And… and about that same time, in the 80s, mid-80s, late 80s,

259
00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:47.110
Julie Stout: I thought, too, you know, this is… I don't like this. I really don't like this. I'm all constantly in a situation, in a context, where they're PhD people, and they're just different, and they seem different anyway. I better do it.

260
00:37:47.610 --> 00:37:48.690
Julie Stout: So I did.

261
00:37:49.290 --> 00:38:07.790
Julie Stout: And by then, I had… I had, since I had written my… my master's degree on my grandfather's life, the history of Latvia had… had come forth, and then also the history of the people who came here, moved here, came forth in the work that I was doing, and…

262
00:38:08.040 --> 00:38:15.070
Julie Stout: So I realized that I would write the dissertation on being exile.

263
00:38:15.290 --> 00:38:26.509
Julie Stout: And that's… that's what motivated it in the end, so that's how I got into Latvia. And a lot of field work and grants and so on to go to Latvia to do research.

264
00:38:29.270 --> 00:38:31.850
Julie Stout: So I thank Linda Daig for that.

265
00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:36.719
Julie Stout: She basically kind of, like, pushed you to do that.

266
00:38:38.210 --> 00:38:48.930
Julie Stout: How did it feel going back to, like, the country that you were born in, but you don't remember that most of because of everything that happened, like, politically, militarily?

267
00:38:48.980 --> 00:39:13.090
Julie Stout: What was that experience like for you? Well, you'd heard so much here. I mean, the community was so active. We had, you know, musicians who were playing, Latvian musicians playing, becoming trios, doing this, doing that. There were people who were writing books, there were theater productions in Indianapolis, so it was… it was a whole world of Latvia here, and because they had lost

268
00:39:13.700 --> 00:39:21.229
Julie Stout: lost it in their eyes. They had lost it. They were exiles. They had… they were not immigrants. They hadn't done this on purpose.

269
00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:30.949
Julie Stout: They were pretty fierce in their loyalty and… and their… their emotions about Latvia.

270
00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:41.159
Julie Stout: So, going back there was… was a big deal. It was a big deal for my family as well as me, because they had not been back.

271
00:39:41.550 --> 00:39:54.849
Julie Stout: In all those years. My uncle did visit us here in the United States, which was pretty amazing, really, since he got out. But he went back to his family.

272
00:39:55.090 --> 00:40:17.540
Julie Stout: So, I went there with… with that kind of a… both a burden and a curiosity. And my father, of course, was in Latvia. So, I went the first time in 1983, before I turned 40. I… I just decided for myself I didn't want to be 40 and not have… You went the first time to Latvia?

273
00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:26.859
Julie Stout: 19… I was… I was 39, so, it was 1983, I think. 1983. 1983. Oh, 39.

274
00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:29.690
Julie Stout: At 39 years old?

275
00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:31.290
Julie Stout: You said? Yeah. Okay.

276
00:40:31.530 --> 00:40:32.750
Julie Stout: 39.

277
00:40:33.400 --> 00:40:44.169
Julie Stout: So that was one big deal. I met my uncle… I'd already met my uncles, and I stayed at his house for 6 weeks, and I met my father, and

278
00:40:44.800 --> 00:40:54.149
Julie Stout: So that was good, and then he had two children by then, so I had a half-brother and a half-sister. And when I arrived at the airport in Riga.

279
00:40:54.400 --> 00:40:57.840
Julie Stout: I think some 35 people showed up to meet me.

280
00:40:58.080 --> 00:41:01.340
Julie Stout: That's how the family had grown. Wow. Yeah.

281
00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:03.340
Julie Stout: I'd met two of them.

282
00:41:03.680 --> 00:41:14.949
Julie Stout: Two of those. A lot of, lot of people, some people my age, but most of the children were younger at that point. Just extended family, I'm guessing? Family friends?

283
00:41:15.360 --> 00:41:20.969
Julie Stout: Yeah, extended family of 3 families. My mother had… my mother had remarried.

284
00:41:21.140 --> 00:41:35.399
Julie Stout: here, and he had a wife and a daughter left there, and they had grown and married and had children. My father had a family, he had remarried, had kids, and, my mother.

285
00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:55.010
Julie Stout: Had a family and kids, so there were plenty of people to meet. And I… one of the most… what I really remembered very brightly is just a tiny little incident, and that was little kids riding by me on… in bicycles and talking Latvian.

286
00:41:55.040 --> 00:42:03.579
Julie Stout: And I couldn't believe it. They really… there really are people who talk Latvian. This is in Latvia. Yeah, this is in Latvia.

287
00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:23.200
Julie Stout: There really are, because for me, I spoke English. I didn't really speak Latvian all that easily, or I didn't want to. Although, in high school, only Latvians were my friends. They were all my friends, and I didn't really make American friends, so that was kind of an odd period, too, but…

288
00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:38.740
Julie Stout: But just to hear them actually speaking Latvian, so it's real. It brought back, like, memories for you, or just, like… No, just, just… It just kind of hit you? This was just an imagined, world, I think. It was really just an imagined world.

289
00:42:39.360 --> 00:42:46.660
Julie Stout: You know, that was called Latvia. It really didn't mean all that much to me. It did… I knew it did to my family.

290
00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:50.140
Julie Stout: So, makes sense.

291
00:42:51.120 --> 00:42:59.670
Julie Stout: Did your mom move back to Latvia at some point, or did she say… She visited twice. Okay, she visited with you, I'm guessing, or…

292
00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:16.059
Julie Stout: she… she visited… she and her husband went, and they went to his house, and his wife said to him, my, you've grown old. No, she said… he said that to her. He said that to her. I… I was… I was mad at him. I told him, you don't do that, little woman.

293
00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:19.099
Julie Stout: In my, you've grown old.

294
00:43:19.810 --> 00:43:29.590
Julie Stout: And with my father, he recognized him before my mother did. Really? Yes. He said, well, I think that that's Fred.

295
00:43:30.220 --> 00:43:40.899
Julie Stout: They had… they had a good time, I think, and my father was a fairly amazing man. I… I really got to know him very, very, very well.

296
00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:45.680
Julie Stout: In my 40-plus years. When you visited for the first time.

297
00:43:45.760 --> 00:44:03.889
Julie Stout: Well, no, I mean over the years after that, over the years after that, because I was there very often, almost every other year, because I was working on field work for the dissertation, and then I'd made so many friends and relatives, friends, that I just kept going.

298
00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:06.740
Julie Stout: And there was a time when I thought.

299
00:44:06.810 --> 00:44:27.689
Julie Stout: could I live here? And I realized I couldn't… I was just about to ask you. Yeah, I couldn't. It was too small, even though it's about the size of Indiana, but it's too small, because everybody was Latvian, and there was no diversity, really, to speak of, and there was no rest of the United States, and Montana, and New York, and Maine, and so on, you know?

300
00:44:28.670 --> 00:44:32.960
Julie Stout: So… When, do you still travel to Latvia?

301
00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:36.310
Julie Stout: I… my…

